@node Overview
@chapter Overview

AI coding agents such as @uref{https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code, Claude Code} and @uref{https://openai.com/index/introducing-codex/, Codex} store complete conversation transcripts as JSONL files.  While these files contain a full record of every session, they are not human-readable: each line is a JSON object with nested content arrays, tool-use blocks, thinking sections, and system metadata.  @samp{agent-log.el} renders these transcripts into readable Markdown files and provides a dedicated Emacs interface for browsing, searching, and navigating them.

The package supports multiple backends through a generic interface based on @code{cl-defstruct} and @code{cl-defmethod}.  Each backend knows how to discover sessions, parse its tool's JSONL format, and normalize entries into a canonical representation that the rendering pipeline, session browser, and AI features operate on.  Currently supported backends are Claude Code (@samp{agent-log-claude.el}) and Codex (@samp{agent-log-codex.el}).  By default, the package auto-detects which tools are installed and activates the corresponding backends (@ref{Backend configuration}).

The package maintains a mirror directory of pre-rendered Markdown files, organized by project.  This means that standard tools such as @samp{consult-ripgrep}, Dired, and @samp{grep} work natively on readable content without any special integration.

The core capabilities of @samp{agent-log.el} are:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Session browsing}.  A @code{completing-read} interface lists all sessions, grouped by project or as a flat list, sorted by recency.  Each candidate shows the date, project name, and either an AI-generated summary or the first user message (@ref{Session browsing}).
@item
@strong{Lazy rendering}.  Sessions are rendered to @samp{.md} files on first access.  The package tracks JSONL file sizes in an index to avoid re-rendering files that have not changed (@ref{Sync and rendering}).
@item
@strong{Live updates}.  For active sessions, a @code{file-notify} watcher detects JSONL changes and appends new entries to both the @samp{.md} file on disk and the open buffer in real time (@ref{Live updates}).
@item
@strong{Outline navigation}.  Rendered buffers use @code{outline-minor-mode} for folding tool calls, thinking blocks, and tool results.  Dedicated keybindings jump between conversation turns (@ref{Navigation}).
@item
@strong{Smart tool summaries}.  Each tool call is summarized by its most relevant input—the file path for Read/Write, the command for Bash, the pattern for Grep, and so on.
@item
@strong{AI-powered session summaries}.  An optional integration with @samp{gptel} generates concise one-line and paragraph summaries for each session, displayed in the browser and at the top of rendered buffers (@ref{Summary generation}).
@item
@strong{AI-powered search}.  A two-stage LLM pipeline lets you search your session history with natural language queries.  A scope-narrowing model filters sessions by project and date range, then a selection model identifies the most relevant sessions and presents a narrative with clickable links (@ref{AI search}).
@item
@strong{Session resumption}.  You can resume any session directly in the coding agent from within the rendered buffer, provided the corresponding Emacs integration package is installed (e.g. @samp{claude-code} for Claude Code) (@ref{Session resumption}).
@end itemize

The package requires Emacs 29.1 or later and @uref{https://jblevins.org/projects/markdown-mode/, markdown-mode} 2.6 or later.  The optional summary feature requires @uref{https://github.com/karthink/gptel, gptel}.  Session resumption for Claude Code sessions requires @uref{https://github.com/stevemolitor/claude-code.el, claude-code}.

The development repository is on @uref{https://github.com/benthamite/agent-log, GitHub}.

@node Installation
@chapter Installation

@menu
