@node Backend configuration
@section Backend configuration

@vindex agent-log-backends
@vindex agent-log-active-backends

The user option @code{agent-log-backends} is an alist mapping backend key symbols to their feature (file) names.  Each entry is a cons cell @samp{(KEY . FEATURE)} where @samp{KEY} is a symbol identifying the backend (e.g. @code{claude-code}, @code{codex}) and @samp{FEATURE} is the symbol passed to @code{require} to load the backend file.  Backend files are loaded lazily on first use.  The default value includes entries for Claude Code and Codex:

@lisp
'((claude-code . agent-log-claude)
  (codex . agent-log-codex))
@end lisp

You would modify this to add a custom backend or to remove a backend you do not want available.

The user option @code{agent-log-active-backends} controls which backends are scanned for sessions.  It accepts either the symbol @code{auto} or a list of backend key symbols.  When set to @code{auto} (the default), the package checks whether each backend's root directory exists on disk (e.g. @samp{~/.claude} for Claude Code, @samp{~/.codex} for Codex) and activates only the backends whose directories are found.  Set it to an explicit list such as @code{(claude-code)} if you want to restrict the session browser to a specific backend regardless of what is installed.

@node Directory configuration
@section Directory configuration

@vindex agent-log-directory
@vindex agent-log-rendered-directory

The user option @code{agent-log-directory} specifies the root directory of the Claude Code backend's configuration.  The package reads @samp{history.jsonl} in this directory and looks for session files under the @samp{projects/} subdirectory.  The default value is @samp{~/.claude}.  You would change this only if you have configured Claude Code to use a non-standard location.  Each backend has its own directory configuration.

The user option @code{agent-log-rendered-directory} specifies the directory where rendered Markdown files are stored.  Each project gets its own subdirectory, and each session is rendered as a dated @samp{.md} file within it (@ref{Sync and rendering}).  The default value is @samp{~/.claude/rendered}.  You might change this if you want rendered files to live outside the default configuration directory, for example on a path indexed by a desktop search tool.

@node Display of thinking and tool sections
@section Display of thinking and tool sections

@vindex agent-log-show-thinking
@vindex agent-log-show-tools

Agent conversations contain thinking blocks (the model's chain-of-thought reasoning) and tool-use sections (file reads, bash commands, grep searches, and so on).  These are valuable for understanding what the assistant did, but they can also be verbose and clutter the view when you are reading the high-level conversation.

The user option @code{agent-log-show-thinking} controls how thinking blocks appear.  It accepts one of three symbols:

@itemize
@item
@code{hidden}: thinking blocks are omitted entirely from the rendered output.
@item
@code{collapsed}: thinking blocks are rendered but folded under a heading, so you see the heading but not the content until you expand it.
@item
@code{visible}: thinking blocks are rendered fully expanded.
@end itemize

The default value is @code{collapsed}.

The user option @code{agent-log-show-tools} works identically but controls tool-use and tool-result sections.  It also defaults to @code{collapsed}.

When both options are set to @code{hidden}, assistant turns that contain only tool calls and thinking (no visible text) are hidden entirely, including their heading and separator.

You can toggle individual sections interactively using @code{agent-log-toggle-section} (@ref{Section visibility}).

@node Timestamps
@section Timestamps

@vindex agent-log-timestamp-format

The user option @code{agent-log-timestamp-format} controls the format string used when displaying timestamps in rendered output.  It follows the conventions of @code{format-time-string}.  The default value is @samp{"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"}.

@node Tool output limits
@section Tool output limits

@vindex agent-log-max-tool-input-length
@vindex agent-log-max-tool-result-length

Tool calls can have very long inputs (entire file contents for Write, lengthy commands for Bash) and even longer results.  Two user options control how much of this content is shown in the rendered output.

The user option @code{agent-log-max-tool-input-length} sets the maximum number of characters displayed for tool input summaries.  Text beyond this limit is truncated with an ellipsis.  The default value is @code{200}.

The user option @code{agent-log-max-tool-result-length} sets the maximum number of characters displayed for tool result content.  The default value is @code{500}.

Increase these values if you find that truncated tool content is hiding information you need.  Decrease them if rendered files are too large or buffers are slow to navigate.

@node Session browser options
@section Session browser options

@vindex agent-log-group-by-project
@vindex agent-log-display-width
@vindex agent-log-slug-max-length

The user option @code{agent-log-group-by-project} controls whether @code{agent-log-browse-sessions} groups sessions by project (@ref{Session browsing}).  When non-@code{nil} (the default), the command first prompts for a project, then for a session within that project.  When @code{nil}, all sessions are presented in a single flat list.  The grouped view is more convenient when you have many sessions across several projects; the flat view is useful for quickly finding a recent session regardless of project.

The user option @code{agent-log-display-width} sets the maximum width of the first-message column in the session browser.  Longer messages are truncated.  The default value is @code{60}.

The user option @code{agent-log-slug-max-length} sets the maximum length of the slug portion of rendered filenames.  The slug is derived from the first user message and appears after the date in the filename (e.g., @samp{2026-02-22_11-56_redesign-agent-log-package.md}).  The default value is @code{50}.

@node Live updates
@section Live updates

@vindex agent-log-live-update

The user option @code{agent-log-live-update} controls whether the package watches the source JSONL file for changes when a rendered buffer is open.  When non-@code{nil} (the default), a @code{file-notify} watcher detects new entries appended to the JSONL file and renders them into both the open buffer and the @samp{.md} file on disk.  This means you can have a rendered log open alongside an active coding agent session and see new turns appear as they happen.

Set this to @code{nil} if you experience performance issues with file watching, or if you are on a system where @code{file-notify} is not reliable (e.g., certain remote filesystems via TRAMP).

@node Summary generation (1)
@section Summary generation

@vindex agent-log-summary-backend
@vindex agent-log-summary-model
@vindex agent-log-summary-max-content-length

The summary feature uses @samp{gptel} to generate concise descriptions of each session.  Three user options control how summaries are generated.

The user option @code{agent-log-summary-backend} specifies the @samp{gptel} backend name to use for summary requests, for example @samp{"Gemini"} or @samp{"Claude"}.  When @code{nil} (the default), the backend is inferred from @code{agent-log-summary-model} if set, otherwise it falls back to @code{gptel-backend}.

The user option @code{agent-log-summary-model} specifies the @samp{gptel} model to use, for example @code{claude-haiku-4-5-20251001}.  A smaller, faster model is often sufficient for summarization.  When @code{nil} (the default), it uses @code{gptel-model}.

The user option @code{agent-log-summary-max-content-length} sets the maximum number of characters of conversation text sent to the LLM for summarization.  The package extracts the plain text of user and assistant messages (ignoring tool calls and thinking blocks) and truncates the result to this limit.  The default value is @code{8000}.  Increase this for longer, more detailed summaries at the cost of higher token usage; decrease it if you want to minimize API costs.

@node AI search options
@section AI search options

@vindex agent-log-search-scope-backend
@vindex agent-log-search-scope-model
@vindex agent-log-search-backend
@vindex agent-log-search-model
@vindex agent-log-search-budget

The AI search feature (@ref{AI search}) uses two LLM calls: a scope-narrowing stage and a selection stage.  Each stage has its own backend and model options, allowing you to use a cheap, fast model for scope narrowing and a more capable model for the selection narrative.

The user option @code{agent-log-search-scope-backend} specifies the @samp{gptel} backend for stage 1 (scope narrowing), for example @samp{"Gemini"} or @samp{"Claude"}.  When @code{nil} (the default), the backend is inferred from @code{agent-log-search-scope-model} if set, otherwise it falls back to @code{gptel-backend}.

The user option @code{agent-log-search-scope-model} specifies the model for stage 1.  A small, fast model (e.g. @code{claude-haiku-4-5-20251001}) is recommended since the task is simple classification.  When @code{nil} (the default), it uses @code{gptel-model}.

The user option @code{agent-log-search-backend} specifies the @samp{gptel} backend for stage 2 (selection and narrative).  When @code{nil} (the default), the backend is inferred from @code{agent-log-search-model} if set, otherwise it falls back to @code{gptel-backend}.

The user option @code{agent-log-search-model} specifies the model for stage 2.  This model receives all filtered session summaries and must reason over them, so a more capable model may produce better results.  When @code{nil} (the default), it uses @code{gptel-model}.

The user option @code{agent-log-search-budget} sets a per-request cost threshold as a @samp{(TYPE . LIMIT)} cons cell, where @samp{TYPE} is either @code{tokens} or @code{dollars}.  Before stage 2 sends the filtered summaries to the LLM, the package estimates the prompt's token count (heuristically, one token per four characters).  If the estimate exceeds the limit, the user is asked to confirm with @code{y-or-n-p}.  The default value is @code{(tokens . 50000)}.

In @code{dollars} mode, cost estimation requires the @samp{gptel-plus} package.  If @samp{gptel-plus} is not available, the budget is not enforced and a warning is displayed.  Dollar estimates use the model's input pricing from @samp{gptel-plus} to convert the estimated token count to a dollar amount.

