@node Session browsing
@section Session browsing

@findex agent-log-browse-sessions
@findex agent-log-open-latest
@findex agent-log-open-file
@findex agent-log-open-session
@findex agent-log-open-session-at-point

The command @code{agent-log-browse-sessions} is the primary entry point for exploring your session history.  It reads @samp{history.jsonl}, resolves each session to its JSONL file on disk, and presents the results in a @code{completing-read} prompt.  Each candidate is formatted as:

@example
2026-02-22 14:06  my-project  "Fix the authentication bug in..."
@end example

When @code{agent-log-group-by-project} is non-@code{nil} (the default), the command first prompts for a project, then for a session within that project (@ref{Session browser options}).  Sessions are sorted most-recent-first.  If AI summaries have been generated for any sessions (@ref{Summary generation}), the summary replaces the quoted first message in the candidate display.

Selecting a session lazily renders it to a @samp{.md} file if needed, then opens the rendered buffer in @code{agent-log-mode} (@ref{@code{agent-log-mode}}).

The command @code{agent-log-open-latest} opens the most recent session directly, without prompting.  This is convenient when you want to review the last conversation you had with a coding agent.

The command @code{agent-log-open-file} opens a specific JSONL file by path.  It prompts for a file path interactively.  This is useful for automation, for opening session files you found via the filesystem, or when you know the exact file you want.

The command @code{agent-log-open-session} opens a session by its ID@.  It prompts for the session ID interactively.

The command @code{agent-log-open-session-at-point} opens the log for the Claude Code session running in the current buffer.  This command is defined in @samp{agent-log-claude.el} and requires the @samp{claude-code} package; the current buffer must be a Claude Code terminal buffer.  The command reads the status file that Claude Code writes to @samp{/tmp/claude-code-status/} and uses the @samp{transcript_path} field to locate the exact JSONL file for the session.  This uniquely identifies the session even when multiple sessions (including branches created with @code{/branch}) share the same project directory.  If the status file is unavailable, it falls back to the most recently modified JSONL file in the project's session directory, or to searching @samp{history.jsonl}.  This lets you quickly jump from an active Claude Code session to its rendered log.

@node Rendered directory
@section Rendered directory

@findex agent-log-open-rendered-directory

The command @code{agent-log-open-rendered-directory} opens the rendered Markdown directory in Dired.  Since rendered files are plain Markdown organized by project, you can use standard Emacs tools to browse, search, and manage them.  For example, you can run @samp{consult-ripgrep} from this Dired buffer to search across all rendered sessions.

If the rendered directory does not yet exist, the command creates it.

@node Sync and rendering
@section Sync and rendering

@findex agent-log-sync-all
@findex agent-log-refresh

By default, rendering is lazy: sessions are rendered to @samp{.md} files on first access via @code{agent-log-browse-sessions} or @code{agent-log-open-file}.  The package maintains an index file (@samp{_index.el}) in the rendered directory that maps session IDs to rendered file paths and JSONL file sizes.  When you access a session, the package compares the current JSONL file size against the indexed size; if they differ, the session is re-rendered.

The command @code{agent-log-sync-all} renders all unrendered or stale sessions in bulk.  It processes sessions one at a time using @code{run-with-timer} to avoid blocking Emacs.  A progress message reports how many sessions were rendered.

The command @code{agent-log-refresh} re-renders the session displayed in the current buffer from its JSONL source.  This is useful if the rendered file appears stale or if you have changed display settings such as @code{agent-log-show-thinking} or @code{agent-log-show-tools} (@ref{Display of thinking and tool sections}).  The keybinding is @samp{g} in @code{agent-log-mode}.

@node Navigation
@section Navigation

@findex agent-log-next-turn
@findex agent-log-previous-turn

The command @code{agent-log-next-turn} moves point to the next User or Assistant heading in the buffer.  The command @code{agent-log-previous-turn} moves to the previous one.  These commands search for @samp{## User} and @samp{## Assistant} headings, skipping over tool calls and thinking sections.

The keybindings are @samp{n} and @samp{p} in @code{agent-log-mode}, making it easy to step through a conversation turn by turn.

@node Section visibility
@section Section visibility

@findex agent-log-toggle-section
@findex agent-log-collapse-all-tools
@findex agent-log-expand-all

The command @code{agent-log-toggle-section} toggles the visibility of the section at point.  When point is on a @samp{####} heading (tool call, tool result, or thinking block), it collapses or expands just that section.  When point is on any other heading, it delegates to @code{outline-toggle-children}.  The keybinding is @samp{TAB}.

The command @code{agent-log-collapse-all-tools} collapses all tool-use, tool-result, and thinking sections in the buffer at once.  This gives you a clean view of just the user messages and assistant text responses.  The keybinding is @samp{C}.

The command @code{agent-log-expand-all} expands all sections, removing all section overlays and showing the full content.  The keybinding is @samp{E}.

@node Copying
@section Copying

@findex agent-log-copy-turn

The command @code{agent-log-copy-turn} copies the current turn to the kill ring.  A ``turn'' is delimited by @samp{##} headings: from the current @samp{## User} or @samp{## Assistant} heading up to (but not including) the next one.  This is useful for extracting a specific message from a conversation to paste elsewhere.  The keybinding is @samp{w}.

@node Summary generation
@section Summary generation

@findex agent-log-summarize-sessions
@findex agent-log-stop-summarizing

The command @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions} generates AI summaries for all sessions that do not yet have one.  It requires the @samp{gptel} package.  The command processes sessions sequentially, sending each conversation's text to the configured LLM (@ref{Summary generation (1), , Summary generation options}) and storing the response in the index.  Summary requests disable @code{gptel-use-tools} so that globally configured tools (e.g. MCP servers) are not included in the request.

Each summary consists of two parts: a one-line summary (up to 80 characters) used in the session browser display, and a paragraph summary (3--5 sentences) shown at the top of rendered buffers.  The LLM is instructed to return a JSON object with @code{oneline} and @code{summary} fields.

Progress is displayed in the echo area, showing which session is being summarized and the model in use.  If you invoke @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions} while summarization is already running, it stops the current run instead.  You can also stop explicitly with @code{agent-log-stop-summarizing}.

Summaries are persisted in the index file, so they survive across Emacs sessions and do not need to be regenerated.  When you open a session that has a summary, the paragraph summary is inserted as a blockquote below the session header.

@menu
* Automatic summarization on session end::
@end menu

@node Automatic summarization on session end
@subsection Automatic summarization on session end

@vindex agent-log-sync-on-session-end

When @code{agent-log-sync-on-session-end} is non-nil, @code{agent-log-sync-all} and @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions} run automatically each time a Claude Code session terminates.  This requires the @samp{claude-code} package and a @samp{Stop} hook configured in Claude Code's settings (see the @samp{claude-code} documentation for hook setup).  The hook handler (@code{agent-log-claude--session-end-handler}) is defined in @samp{agent-log-claude.el} and is installed via @code{eval-after-load} when the defcustom is set before the backend is loaded.

Sessions with a live agent process are excluded from summarization by session ID@.  Each backend's @code{agent-log--active-session-ids} method provides the IDs of currently running sessions.  If summarization is already running when another session ends, the in-progress batch continues undisturbed.

@node Session rename
@section Session rename

@findex agent-log-rename-sessions
@vindex agent-log-auto-rename-sessions

The user option @code{agent-log-auto-rename-sessions} controls whether sessions are renamed automatically when they receive an AI summary.  When set to non-@code{nil}, each time @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions} successfully generates a summary for a session, the one-line summary is slugified and written as a @samp{custom-title} entry in the session JSONL file.  This makes the name immediately visible in Claude Code's @samp{/resume} picker without any manual step.

The default value is @code{nil}.  Set it to @code{t} if you want session names to stay in sync with summaries automatically.

The command @code{agent-log-rename-sessions} renames all sessions that lack a custom title.  This command is defined in @samp{agent-log-claude.el} because custom-title entries are a Claude Code-specific JSONL convention.  For each session that has a one-line summary in the index but no @samp{custom-title} entry in its JSONL file, the command writes the summary directly as the custom title.  With a prefix argument (@samp{C-u}), it overwrites existing custom titles as well, which is useful after changing the title format.

This is a purely local, offline operation — no API calls are made.  Sessions must be summarized first via @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions} (@ref{Summary generation}).  Sessions that already have a custom title (e.g. from Claude Code's @samp{/rename} command) are skipped.

After writing custom-title entries, the cached JSONL file sizes in the index are updated in a single bulk write so that @code{agent-log-sync-all} does not treat the modified files as stale and trigger unnecessary re-renders.

The command reports how many sessions were renamed, how many were skipped, and how many lacked a summary.

@node AI search
@section AI search

@findex agent-log-search
@findex agent-log-search-follow-link

The command @code{agent-log-search} searches your session history using natural language.  It prompts for a query string (e.g., ``how did I implement the caching layer?'' or ``conversations about authentication in my web app last month'') and uses a two-stage LLM pipeline to find relevant sessions.

@strong{Stage 1: scope narrowing.}  The query, along with a summary of the archive's metadata (project names with session counts, date range), is sent to a scope-narrowing model.  This model returns structured JSON specifying which projects and date range to include.  If the query does not mention a specific project or timeframe, all sessions are included.  The model and backend for this stage are configured via @code{agent-log-search-scope-model} and @code{agent-log-search-scope-backend} (@ref{AI search options}).

@strong{Stage 2: selection and narrative.}  The filtered session summaries (one-line and paragraph, from @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions}) are sent to a selection model along with the original query.  This model produces a Markdown narrative explaining which sessions are relevant and why, with inline links to specific sessions.  If more than 100 sessions pass the scope filter, only the 100 most recent are sent.  The model and backend for this stage are configured via @code{agent-log-search-model} and @code{agent-log-search-backend} (@ref{AI search options}).

The result is displayed in a @samp{*agent-log-search*} buffer in @code{agent-log-search-mode} (@ref{@code{agent-log-search-mode}}).  Session references in the narrative are rendered as clickable links.  Pressing @samp{RET} or clicking on a link opens the corresponding rendered session log.

Before starting, the command checks for unsummarized sessions.  If any exist, it warns the user that those sessions will be excluded and asks for confirmation.  If no sessions have summaries at all, the command aborts with a message to run @code{agent-log-summarize-sessions} first (@ref{Summary generation}).

Before stage 2, the estimated token cost is compared against @code{agent-log-search-budget} (@ref{AI search options}).  If the estimate exceeds the threshold, the user is asked to confirm.

@node Session resumption
@section Session resumption

@findex agent-log-resume-session

The command @code{agent-log-resume-session} resumes the session displayed in the current buffer in the coding agent.  The command extracts the session ID from the buffer (either from the buffer-local variable or from the front-matter comment) and dispatches to the buffer's backend via the @code{agent-log--resume-session} generic function.  For Claude Code sessions, this requires the @samp{claude-code} package and passes the session ID with the @samp{--resume} flag, starting in the session's project directory when possible.  The keybinding is @samp{r} in @code{agent-log-mode}.

@node @code{agent-log-mode}
@chapter @code{agent-log-mode}

@findex agent-log-mode

@code{agent-log-mode} is the major mode used for rendered session buffers.  It derives from @code{markdown-view-mode}, inheriting Markdown fontification in a read-only buffer.  Buffers are never marked as modified, so @samp{q} (@code{quit-window}) closes them without prompting to save.  The mode activates @code{outline-minor-mode} with a regexp that matches Markdown headings (=## =, =### =, =#### =), enabling section folding.

Two invisibility specs are added: @code{agent-log-collapsed} (which shows the heading but hides the body) and @code{agent-log-hidden} (which hides both heading and body).  These are used by the section visibility commands (@ref{Section visibility}) and the display configuration options (@ref{Display of thinking and tool sections}).

When a buffer in this mode is killed, the file watcher is cleaned up and the index is updated with the final JSONL file size.

