@node Backend architecture
@section Backend architecture

The package uses a generic interface to support multiple AI coding agents.  The base type @code{agent-log-backend} (defined with @code{cl-defstruct}) provides shared slots for the backend name, key symbol, root directory, and rendered directory.  Each backend extends this type via @code{:include} and implements a set of generic functions (@code{cl-defgeneric} / @code{cl-defmethod}) that handle backend-specific operations: session discovery, JSONL entry normalization, conversation filtering, tool input summarization, and session resumption.

Backend files are loaded lazily.  When a backend is first accessed (e.g. during @code{agent-log-browse-sessions}), the package calls @code{require} on the backend's feature name and the backend registers a singleton instance in a global registry.  The registry maps backend key symbols to struct instances, so all dispatch goes through the struct's type.

The rendering pipeline, session browser, live update mechanism, AI summaries, and AI search all operate on a normalized intermediate representation.  Each backend's @code{agent-log--normalize-entries} method converts its native JSONL format into canonical plists that the generic code expects.  Core functions such as @code{agent-log--render-to-file} and @code{agent-log--extract-conversation-text} receive a backend instance and thread it through to generic dispatch points (conversation filtering, entry classification, tool summarization, text extraction).  The convenience function @code{agent-log--read-all-sessions} returns sessions from the first active backend; individual buffers store their backend in the buffer-local variable @code{agent-log--backend}, set when a session is opened.  This means the core of the package is backend-agnostic: adding a new backend requires only implementing the generic functions, with no changes to the core file.

@node Data sources
@section Data sources

The Claude Code backend reads conversation data from two places:

@enumerate
@item
@samp{~/.claude/history.jsonl}: a global index mapping session IDs to projects and timestamps.
@item
@samp{~/.claude/projects/<encoded-path>/<uuid>.jsonl}: one file per session, containing all messages as JSON lines.
@end enumerate

The encoded path replaces @samp{/}, @samp{.}, and space characters with @samp{-}.  The package tries both the expanded path and its @code{file-truename} when locating a session directory, which handles symlinked project paths.

@node Rendered directory structure
@section Rendered directory structure

The rendered directory mirrors the project structure:

@example
~/.claude/rendered/
  tango-wiki/
    2026-02-04_14-06_fix-the-authentication-bug.md
    2026-02-05_09-22_refactor-database-schema.md
  dotfiles/
    2026-02-22_11-56_redesign-agent-log-package.md
  _index.el
@end example

Each @samp{.md} file contains HTML-comment front matter (session ID, source path, rendered timestamp, JSONL size) followed by the full conversation rendered as Markdown.  The @samp{_index.el} file is a hash table mapping session IDs to metadata (rendered file path, JSONL size, and optionally a summary).

@node Rendering pipeline
@section Rendering pipeline

Each JSONL entry has a @code{type} field: @code{user}, @code{assistant}, @code{progress}, @code{system}, or @code{file-history-snapshot}.  The package filters entries via the backend's @code{agent-log--filter-conversation} and @code{agent-log--conversation-entry-p} methods, which select @code{user} and @code{assistant} entries while excluding system-generated messages.  For Claude Code, system entries are those whose content starts with known XML tags such as @samp{<local-command-stdout>} or @samp{<command-name>}.

Filtered entries are rendered as Markdown with @samp{##} headings for conversation turns and @samp{####} headings for tool calls and thinking blocks.  User turns show any text content followed by tool results.  Assistant turns show thinking blocks, text content, and tool-use summaries.

The session header (the @samp{# Session: ...} line at the top of each rendered file) derives its project name from the @code{progress} entry in the JSONL, which contains the working directory.  Not all sessions have a @code{progress} entry; when one is absent, the package falls back to the project path recorded in @samp{history.jsonl}.

@node Live update mechanism
@section Live update mechanism

When @code{agent-log-live-update} is non-@code{nil} and a rendered buffer is open, the package registers a @code{file-notify} watcher on the source JSONL file.  When the file grows, the watcher reads only the new bytes (from the previously recorded offset to the new file size), handling incomplete UTF-8 sequences at chunk boundaries.  New complete lines are parsed and rendered incrementally, appended to both the buffer and the @samp{.md} file on disk.

@node Troubleshooting
@chapter Troubleshooting

@menu
* No sessions found::
* Rendered files not updating::
* Live updates not working::
@end menu

@node No sessions found
@section No sessions found

Ensure that @code{agent-log-directory} points to the correct configuration directory (@ref{Directory configuration}).  The package reads @samp{history.jsonl} in that directory and looks for session files under @samp{projects/}.

@node Rendered files not updating
@section Rendered files not updating

If a rendered file appears stale, press @samp{g} (@code{agent-log-refresh}) in the buffer to force a full re-render (@ref{Sync and rendering}).  You can also delete the index file (@samp{_index.el} in the rendered directory) to force re-rendering of all sessions on next access.

@node Live updates not working
@section Live updates not working

Verify that @code{agent-log-live-update} is set to @code{t} (@ref{Live updates}).  Live updates rely on @code{file-notify}, which requires OS-level file watching support.  On some systems (e.g., remote filesystems via TRAMP), file notifications may not be available.

